Here's how to save/restore draft text using Window lifecycle events:

**Create a custom `Window` subclass in `App.xaml.cs`:**

```csharp
public partial class App : Application
{
    protected override Window CreateWindow(IActivationState? activationState)
        => new AppWindow(new AppShell());
}

public class AppWindow : Window
{
    public AppWindow(Page page) : base(page) { }

    protected override void OnStopped()
    {
        base.OnStopped();
        SaveDraft();
    }

    protected override void OnDestroying()
    {
        base.OnDestroying();
        SaveDraft(); // Android back-button can skip Stopped
    }

    protected override void OnResumed()
    {
        base.OnResumed();
        if (Shell.Current?.CurrentPage is NotePage page)
            page.RestoreDraft();
    }

    private void SaveDraft()
    {
        if (Shell.Current?.CurrentPage is NotePage page)
            Preferences.Set("draft_text", page.GetDraftText());
    }
}
```

**In your `NotePage`:**

```csharp
public partial class NotePage : ContentPage
{
    public NotePage()
    {
        InitializeComponent();
        RestoreDraft(); // Also restore on first load
    }

    public string GetDraftText() => DraftEditor.Text ?? string.Empty;

    public void RestoreDraft()
    {
        DraftEditor.Text = Preferences.Get("draft_text", string.Empty);
    }
}
```

**Key points:**

- **`OnStopped`** fires when the app is fully backgrounded — save here.
- **`OnDestroying`** also saves because Android's back button can skip `Stopped`.
- **`OnResumed`** fires when returning from background (not on first launch).
- **Keep handlers fast** — `Preferences` is ideal for small text. For large drafts, use file I/O instead.
- **`Resumed` ≠ first launch** — the initial sequence is `Created` → `Activated`, so restore in your page constructor too.
